TY  - JOUR
T1  - Federal Taxes and Homeownership: Evidence from Time Series
AU  - Rosen, Harvey S.
AU  - Rosen, Kenneth T.
Y1  - 1980/02/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260847
DO  - 10.1086/260847
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 59
EP  - 75
VL  - 88
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper analyzes U.S. time-series data in order to study the determinants of the choice between renting and homeownership. Special attention is focused upon changes in the relative prices of owning and renting induced by provisions of the federal personal income tax. The results suggest that about one-quarter of the growth in the proportion of homeowners in the post-World War II period is a consequence of the tax system's favorable treatment of owner-occupied housing.
AB  - This paper analyzes U.S. time-series data in order to study the determinants of the choice between renting and homeownership. Special attention is focused upon changes in the relative prices of owning and renting induced by provisions of the federal personal income tax. The results suggest that about one-quarter of the growth in the proportion of homeowners in the post-World War II period is a consequence of the tax system's favorable treatment of owner-occupied housing.
