TY  - JOUR
T1  - Stochastic Dominance in Human Capital
AU  - Eden, Benjamin
Y1  - 1980/02/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260851
DO  - 10.1086/260851
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 135
EP  - 145
VL  - 88
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The paper considers the choice between two finite income paths that are subject to random variations. It is shown that if one income path, X, has more cumulative variation at the outset and less variation toward the end than another income path, Y, then X dominates Y in the sense that (almost) every decision maker prefers X to Y. The intuitive reasoning is that a decision maker with income path X can, by engaging in a fair gamble, create the random variation of the cumulative income under Y and still have the advantage that more of the uncertainty is resolved at an earlier stage.
AB  - The paper considers the choice between two finite income paths that are subject to random variations. It is shown that if one income path, X, has more cumulative variation at the outset and less variation toward the end than another income path, Y, then X dominates Y in the sense that (almost) every decision maker prefers X to Y. The intuitive reasoning is that a decision maker with income path X can, by engaging in a fair gamble, create the random variation of the cumulative income under Y and still have the advantage that more of the uncertainty is resolved at an earlier stage.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260851
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260851
Y2  - 2024/03/22
